"response_text": "The risk attitude traces in the plot exhibit two primary phases of deviation from recommended livestock levels. Initially, between Steps 0-40, all lines show a relatively constrained variance within ±0.2 units, suggesting agents adjust cautiously to initial environmental conditions. This phase peaks sharply between Steps 40-60 as variance exceeds ±0.3 for most lines, indicating heightened stocking adjustments likely driven by stochastic rainfall events (std=100) and delayed vegetation recovery dynamics (gr1=0.5 growth rate). The abrupt stabilization phase (Steps 70-100) shows variance collapse to <0.1 units across most lines, mirroring the resting threshold parameterization near 0.1 biomass levels. This pattern suggests risk-averse agents (risk-att-init=0.5) converge to conservative herding strategies when facing recurring environmental shocks, creating feedback loops between pasture degradation risks and household resilience metrics. The persistent deviation in lower-numbered lines below -0.1 suggests systematic understocking in certain scenarios, potentially reflecting resource scarcity thresholds below resting-biomass levels."  
}

